Dawn McCormick, one of the techs in the article (I wrote Double Station
Technique) had the same concerns that have been mentioned here. She is very
careful to monitor who she asks to sit 'double,' and has not, since 1999, had  any
complaints on this technique nor lost anyone because of it.
In reality, nail techs seem to really 'know' their clients, their  likes and
dislikes when it comes to service.

It is not happening with every client - it is only with those who  like it,
and believe it or not, the majority of her clients do. They  book with their
friends, or like to meet new people. She is a gel nail tech and  finds this very
conducive to double station technique, though initially she also  did it with
acrylics-just took longer.

It has been a great boon to Dawn's business $$ wise, but in another  reality,
it is not for anyone who does nails 'to have fun,' or is not  willing to work
hard and efficiently. A double station tech works hard, though  it became so
automatic soon for her that she doesn't feel any stress  at all doing it.
She is a very efficient and talented nail tech, has been doing it  for 20+
years ('83?), and is serious about being professional. Her  studio (she works
alone by choice) is on the first floor of a house she  purchased/remodeled in
Columbus OH (in Victorian Village, for those who know  Columbus). She lives in
an apt upstairs and LOVES her commute.

JanMc
