I use a double station setup (L Shaped).  It works great.  I started using
this type of setup over 10 years ago.  At first it started out as just a way
to have my client move to the next station for drying while I got my next
client started.  It was just a means to save a little bit of time.  Then I
started using it to "squeeze" in a repair or polish change here or there.
Eventually I started using it to double book manicures.  With the way I do
my manicures it works out great as I can do 2 manicures in the time it takes
to do 1.  My clients do not mind at all because when I'm with the second
client the first is in "down time" anyway.  I do not use this technique so
much with enhancement services but I specialize in natural nail care anyway
so I have more manicures and pedicures than I do enhancements anyway.  When
I had my salon in FL I also would book 2 pedi clients in the same slot.
This was way before the pedi thrones came about and I had two pedicure
stations (not the pedi thrones) set up side by side and it worked out
wonderfully.  (see my sig line).  This method has really helped me to
increase my income potential without sacrificing the quality of service.
It's also great if 2 friends want to book at the same time but don't want to
spend so long in the salon.   My clients do not feel like their time is
being shortened with me as generally speaking, the two clients and I have
conversations all together....it is a really great way for "socializing".
And quite honestly, I end up being able to work more efficiently because the
2 clients end up talking while I work instead of me having to help carry on
a conversation (hope that made sense LOL).

If anyone's interested I do have a picture of my station setup with 2 tables
on my website.

