Everyone has or has had clients like this. You have to politely but
firmly take control from the very beginning. Think about
it..."professionalism" is an attribute that nail professionals are
trying to get across to the general public these days...it is an issue
with many people in this business. When you are in the personal
service industry some people put you in a certain category, and
"professional" is not it. However, nail professionals ARE
"professionals". Some people in our business don't even want to be
called "nail techs", they want to be called "nail
professionals"....that is how big of an issue this is...but you have
to act  professionally and not tolerate a client treating you like you
are NOT a "professional".

For instance...would you go to the dentist and interupt  him during
the procedure to check out what he is doing and see if you "like" how
he is filling your cavity so far? Of course not. Why? Because you
recognize him as a professional who knows what he is doing and you
leave him alone to do it.  A nail professional should expect the same
thing.

YOu can be gentle about it, but you must be firm. If a customer sits
down for the first time in  your chair....and she wants to point out
whatever is bothering her or whatever she wants to point out...fine.
The first time.  You don't need her to tell you waht is wrong with her
nails, as you as the professional will know once YOU look at them. You
only need her input as to how she wants them to look when the
procedure is finished...shape, length, etc. Otherwise, you don't need
her input.

You should listen to her, and then say okay and go to work. If she
starts to pull her hand away to check out each step....nicely,
politely tell her to give you her hand back and let you go to work.
Tell her she can tell you everything that is wrong when you are done,
or at a point where YOU want her input.

You must be firm and mean what you say. She is wasting your time, and
that means she is taking money right out of your pocket. Just do not
tolerate unnecessary interuptions so she can keep checking on you. If
she keeps it up...put your file down, to get her attention, and say
something like, lets make a deal. You let me go to work uninterupted,
and if anything is wrong when I am done...I will fix it. You must
speak firmly to her and tell her you can not work this way, and that
you are a professional doing nails x amount of  years, and that's
that.

I even, on more than one occasion, have told customers..."you know, my
grandmother used to say 'never show a fool a job half done'". That may
sound harsh, but you may have never had some of the clients I ran
across. I said it with a smile, but they "got it". I don't recommend
that saying but I am just telling you my experience.

One caveat....if you take that attitude you must have the confidence
and the skill to back it up. If you are confident you ARE a
professional and your work DOES hold up to scrutiny...then you must
insist on the same respect any other professional will command.

